ATOC 181	Introduction to Atmospheric Science.	A survey of the Earth's atmosphere, weather and climate system. Topics include the fundamental processes that determine interactions between the atmosphere, ocean and biosphere; anthropogenic effects such as global warming, the ozone hole and acid rain; a perspective on future climate change.	0.0	Atmospheric & Oceanic Sciences (Faculty of Science)	t	f	f		
ATOC 182	Introduction to Oceanic Sciences.	An introduction to ocean sciences with particular emphasis on physical oceanography. Topics typically include seawater properties, sea ice, air-sea interaction, seafloor topography, large-scale ocean circulation, waves, tides, physical control of biological processes, the role of oceans in climate, and impact of human activities.	0.0	Atmospheric & Oceanic Sciences (Faculty of Science)	t	f	f		
ATOC 183	Climate and Climate Change.	The atmosphere, ocean and sea-ice distribution characteristic of the current climate, as seen through observational data and computer model results. Physics of naturally occurring variability on time scales of months to years, such as El Niño. Global circulation models of the atmosphere, ocean and coupled atmosphere-ocean system, and global warming simulations.	0.0	Atmospheric & Oceanic Sciences (Faculty of Science)	f	t	f		
ATOC 184	Science of Storms.	Physical processes associated with severe and hazardous weather affecting the Earth. Topics are taught at a fundamental level, without equations, to provide a complete and up-to-date understanding of such extreme events as blizzards, ice storms, tornadoes, hurricanes, floods and droughts.	0.0	Atmospheric & Oceanic Sciences (Faculty of Science)	f	t	f		
ATOC 185	Natural Disasters.	This course examines the science behind different types of disasters and our ability or inability to control and predict such events. From this course the student will gain an appreciation of natural disasters beyond the newspaper headlines and will better understand how the effects of disasters can be reduced.	0.0	Atmospheric & Oceanic Sciences (Faculty of Science)	t	f	f		
